  "slug": "pecan-bourbon-tart",
  "title": "Pecan and bourbon tart",
  "subtitle": "An American-style pecan filling in a shortcrust case, lifted with bourbon",
  "excerpt": "A deep-filled tart of whole pecans suspended in a glossy bourbon-and-brown-sugar custard, baked until set. Rich, not too sweet, and very good with cream.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Pecan pie is documented in American cooking from the late nineteenth century, with the earliest printed recipes appearing in newspapers from the Gulf Coast states in the 1880s. The inclusion of corn syrup in American recipes dates from the 1920s when Karo began promoting their product. This version uses golden syrup, consistent with British interpretations of the same dish. The bourbon addition follows the Kentucky tradition documented in twentieth-century American regional cookbooks.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "About pecan and bourbon tart",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pecan pie has been made across the American South since the late 1800s. The filling is a custard of eggs, sugar, and golden syrup, with whole pecans stirred through. It sets to a dense, fudgy texture as it bakes. Bourbon is not in every American recipe, but Kentucky cooks have used it for generations. It cuts the sweetness and adds the complexity the filling needs."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The pastry case is ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "blind baked",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmp5q86lz0000i0v4jdo0db27"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " before the filling goes in; this prevents a soggy base under the dense, wet filling. The tart needs to cool for at least two hours after baking, the filling continues to set as it comes to room temperature.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
